{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5c60adbc-16f3-4c4c-b594-81c573598fa0","content":"Since you're using **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** (via `global.json`), you can use the built-in hang detection. Run:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --hang-dump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nThis will automatically terminate and report any test that hangs for more than 5 minutes. The `--` separates `dotnet test` args from the platform args.\n\nYou can also add `--hang-dump-type Mini` or `--hang-dump-type Full` to capture a dump file for post-mortem debugging of the hanging test.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2e6593d9-033b-4c87-aea0-e1dfca5c2256","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is using MSTest with Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner (via global.json). To add a hang timeout of 5 minutes, I can use the `--hang-dump-timeout` option when running tests with `dotnet test`, or configure it in a `.runsettings` file.\n\nSince they're using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP), the hang dump feature is available via the `--hang-dump-timeout` command line option. Let me check what options are available.\n\nFor Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you can use:\n```\ndotnet test --hang-dump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nOr with the platform directly:\n\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --hang-dump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nI'll just show them how to run it with the appropriate command.","outputTokens":317},"id":"d83316cc-9a5a-4c2e-b4cd-7274bf025ac8","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:49:29.226Z","parentId":"2b722f44-2636-4422-a88f-210794a954f5"}
